<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920205-0011</DOCNO><DOCID>920205-0011.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Four Software Firms   To Jointly Develop   An Interface Standard</HL><DATE>02/05/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   AAPL BORL LOTS MSFT NOVL</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><NS>JOINT VENTURES (JVN)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)UTAH (UT)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- Four big software developers have agreedto work jointly in developing a standard for applications insending messages via computer in an apparent effort to thwartindustry leader Microsoft Corp.   Apple Computer Inc., based in Cupertino, Calif., BorlandInternational Inc., Scotts Valley, Calif., Lotus DevelopmentCorp., Cambridge, Mass., and Novell Inc., Provo, Utah, saidthey plan to issue specifications for the so-calledvendor-independent messaging interface next month. Thestandard will reduce confusion created by the variety ofmessage systems used with various computer platforms, thecompanies said.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;It's a tactical move by Lotus to contain Microsoft andthe inroads it's making in work-group applications,&quot; saidDavid Readerman, an analyst with Lehman Brothers Inc.   The four-way agreement is an expansion of a cooperativeeffort announced last September by Lotus that included Appleand International Business Machines Corp. An IBM spokesmansaid the company supports the revised pact.</TEXT></DOC>